    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nIf I already have plugins installed, but then delete the lockfile, then run `nvim -c 'lua vim.pack.update()'`, the lockfile looks like below.\n\n\n\n```\n{\n  \"plugins\": {\n    \"Colorizer\": [],\n    \"debugprint.nvim\": [],\n    \"fileline.nvim\": [],\n    \"firenvim\": [],\n    \"fzf\": [],\n    \"fzf-lua\": [],\n    \"gitsigns.nvim\": [],\n    \"guh.nvim\": [],\n    \"linediff.vim\": [],\n    \"markview.nvim\": [],\n    \"mini.completion\": [],\n    \"nvim-lspconfig\": [],\n    \"nvim-qwahl\": [],\n    \"nvim-repl\": [],\n    \"nvim-treehopper\": [],\n    \"opencode.nvim\": {\n      \"rev\": \"abde303aa435\"\n    },\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n1. Do we need to set `vim.empty_dict()` somewhere to ensure the empty cases are stored as dict `{}` instead of array `[]`?\n2. Is it expected that all plugins which didn't need an update have empty lockfile entries?",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "There is a [documentation to not delete the file](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/a65202e6bd17f5daffaa2d2673128e6fc7b48d5d/runtime/doc/pack.txt#L229). So I guess the question here is how robust to make a recovery from unwanted behavior.\n\nCurrently, necessary lockfile data is computed only at the moment it changes: `src` during install, `rev` during checkout, `version` during change detected in `vim.pack.add()`. Would you expect that in this case (and, as consequence, always) the whole lockfile is computed from scratch?",
